    "body": "I think connecting/advertising local network peers is disabled because some\nclient (cough Parity) was doing it and got VPS clients banned for port\nscanning. So Geth by default does not try to connect to lan peers since the\nmight come from a different lan. There's some netrestrict flag that\ncontrols this. I don't remember all the details though. @fjl?\n\nOn May 11, 2017 05:46, \"koffisam\" <notifications@github.com> wrote:\n\n> So I added the full node address as the --bootnode param and it worked. The\n> hosts discover the bootnode. Only issue is hosts have not yet discovered\n> each other. I suspect it's because my current setup has both on the same\n> local network. I'll test again tomorrow with different port number and if\n> that doesn't work, from different public ips\n> On Wed, May 10, 2017 at 2:50 PM Samson Kirk-Koffi <\n> samson.kirkkoffi@gmail.com> wrote:\n>\n> > Thank you for all your help again. I feel confused. I am trying to setup\n> a\n> > private blockchain:\n> > 1. I created a genesis.json and init'ed all my hosts with it\n> > 2. I started bootnode on the server and passed the address/hash as a\n> > parameter to the other hosts\n> > 3. I made sure all the ports(30303 &30301) are open.\n> > 4. From your recent suggestion I am also running a full node on the\n> server\n> > as well.\n> >\n> > Am I missing something? Please advice.\n> >\n> > On Wed, May 10, 2017 at 9:41 AM, Péter Szilágyi <\n> notifications@github.com>\n> > wrote:\n> >\n> >> Bootnodes just run the UDP discovery protocol, you can't \"addPeer\" them,\n> >> only full nodes can be peered together.\n> >>\n> >> —\n> >> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.\n> >> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> >> <https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/issues/14445#\n> issuecomment-300485162>,\n> >> or mute the thread\n> >> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/\n> AB3f1qQHJ5vPctxBavUoz1OMdUHMJueGks5r4b56gaJpZM4NU0FZ>\n> >> .\n> >>\n> >\n> >\n